    q: "What's the difference between a charbroiler and a grill?",
    a: "Overlapping but distinct. Charbroiler equals a standalone unit with radiant heat over cast iron grates, designed for high-volume char-style cooking with 800 to 1,000°F radiant heat. Grill is often integrated with a range, or a separate unit with different burner geometry. Both produce char marks. Charbroilers are the standalone tier for steakhouses, burger restaurants, BBQ joints, and Korean BBQ where char-cooking is the centerpiece, not a side capability.",
  },
